</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB236FFFFBEFFF4E2CE2E5B794A4A5E" blockId="7.[151,1436,367,538]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="4C0D4D7CFFBEFFF4E2CE2E5B7A6849CC" box="[151,278,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Pseudococcidae" genus="Phenacoccus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutus">
<emphasis id="B979EAEDFFBEFFF4E2CE2E5B7A6849CC" box="[151,278,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">M. hirsutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected twice during the recent survey, once on 
<taxonomicName id="4C0D4D7CFFBEFFF4E1222E5A78A349CC" box="[891,989,368,392]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Hibiscus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B979EAEDFFBEFFF4E1222E5A78A349CC" box="[891,989,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Hibiscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<collectingCountry id="F31A766FFFBEFFF4E65E2E457F4F49C3" box="[1031,1073,367,391]" name="Fiji" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Viti</collectingCountry>
Levu (on which it was common and causing leaf curl) (Suva, Thurston Gardens, 
<date id="FFB3103FFFBEFFF4E0E72EBD784049EB" box="[702,830,407,431]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2009-07-11">
<number id="3DC524D8FFBEFFF4E0E72EBD79A949EB" box="[702,727,407,431]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="11.0">11</number>
.vii. 
<number id="3DC524D8FFBEFFF4E0A62EBD784049EB" box="[767,830,407,431]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</date>
) and once on pineapple on Taveuni (Vinuvasa Estate, 
<date id="FFB3103FFFBEFFF4E2CE2E907A654996" box="[151,283,442,466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2009-07-22">
<number id="3DC524D8FFBEFFF4E2CE2E907BC84996" box="[151,182,442,466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="22.0">22</number>
.vii. 
<number id="3DC524D8FFBEFFF4E2842E907A654996" box="[221,283,442,466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</date>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9C4B0EFFBEFFF4E3762E9079FF4996" author="Williams" box="[303,641,442,466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="17" refString="Williams, D. J. &amp; Watson, G. W. (1988 b) The Scale Insects of the Tropical South Pacific Region. Pt. 2. The Mealybugs (Pseudococcidae). CAB International Institute of Entomology, London. 262 pp." type="book" year="1988" yearSuffix="b">
Williams and Watson (
<number id="3DC524D8FFBEFFF4E0682E9079154996" box="[561,619,442,466]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1988.0">1988</number>
b)
</bibRefCitation>
indicate that it is widespread throughout southern Asia, 
<collectingCountry id="F31A766FFFBEFFF4E75C2E907E154996" box="[1285,1387,442,466]" name="Australia" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Australia</collectingCountry>
and Africa. It is polyphagous and has spread to many geographic areas in recent years. It is a potential invasive pest of several crops, particularly pineapple.
</paragraph>
